    "body": "\n      <p><strong>Purpose:</strong> Redirect is a command script. In EM4 terms, that means it is usually a button the player can press on a person, vehicle, object, or target.</p>\n      <p><strong>Beginner read:</strong> Do not try to understand this script by reading every line at once. First find the script objects, then the command lifecycle functions, then the action queue calls. EM4 scripts are usually built as small checks followed by queued actions.</p>\n\n      <h3>Full copied script</h3>\n      <p>This is a copied documentation snapshot from <code>Scripts/Redirect.script</code>. The live gameplay script was not edited to create this article.</p>\n      <details class=\"source-details\">\n        <summary>Open full source for Redirect.script</summary>\n        <pre><code>//******************************************************************************************\r\n// #Version 1.1#\r\n//\r\n// \t\tChanges: - Compatible with &#39;Lift person&#39; command.\r\n//\r\n//******************************************************************************************\r\n\r\nobject Redirect : CommandScript\r\n{\r\n\tRedirect()\r\n\t{\r\n\t\tSetValidTargets(ACTOR_PERSON);\r\n\t\tSetRestrictions(RESTRICT_SELFEXECUTE);\r\n\t}\r\n\r\n\tbool CheckPossible(GameObject *Caller)\r\n\t{\r\n\t\tif(!Caller-&gt;IsValid() || Caller-&gt;GetType() != ACTOR_PERSON)\r\n\t\t\treturn false;\r\n\t\tPerson p(Caller);\r\n\t\tif(p.IsValid() &amp;&amp; (!p.IsEquipped() || p.GetEquipment() == EQUIP_REDIRECTSIGN) &amp;&amp; !p.IsLinkedWithPerson() &amp;&amp; !p.IsCarryingPerson() &amp;&amp; p.GetEnteredCarID() == -1)\r\n\t\t\treturn true;\r\n\t\treturn false;\r\n\t}\r\n\r\n\tbool CheckTarget(GameObject *Caller, Actor *Target, int childID)\r\n\t{\r\n\t\tif(!Caller-&gt;IsValid() || !Target-&gt;IsValid() || Target-&gt;GetID() != Caller-&gt;GetID())\r\n\t\t\treturn false;\r\n\r\n\t\tPerson p(Caller);\r\n\t\tif(p.IsValid() &amp;&amp; (!p.IsEquipped() || p.GetEquipment() == EQUIP_REDIRECTSIGN) &amp;&amp; !p.IsLinkedWithPerson() &amp;&amp; !p.IsCarryingPerson() &amp;&amp; p.GetEnteredCarID() == -1)\r\n\t\t\treturn true;\r\n\r\n\t\treturn false;\r\n\t}\r\n\r\n\tvoid PushActions(GameObject *Caller, Actor *Target, int childID)\r\n\t{\r\n\t\tCaller-&gt;PushActionRedirect(ACTION_NEWLIST);\r\n\t}\r\n};\r\n</code></pre>\n      </details>\n\n      <h3>Script map</h3>\n      <table><thead><tr><th>Script object</th><th>Base class</th><th>Beginner meaning</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Redirect</td><td>CommandScript</td><td>Player/AI command button logic</td></tr></tbody></table>\n      <p><strong>Detected role tags:</strong> <code>command button</code> <code>action queue</code></p>\n\n      <h3>How EM4 reads this script</h3>\n      <table><thead><tr><th>Function</th><th>What it means</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>CheckPossible</td><td>EM4 calls this before showing or allowing the command. It is usually where the script checks the caller type, equipment state, health, vehicle state, or whether the command should be greyed out.</td></tr><tr><td>CheckTarget</td><td>EM4 calls this after the player points the command at something. This is where the script decides whether the clicked target is valid.</td></tr><tr><td>PushActions</td><td>This is the execution stage. The script normally clears or appends actions here, then sends the caller toward a target, plays an animation, creates/removes objects, or triggers a dummy follow-up command.</td></tr></tbody></table>\n      <p>If this is a command script, EM4 normally asks three questions: should the command be possible, is the clicked target valid, and what actions should be pushed once the player confirms it. If this is a mission script, look for startup/update/timer logic instead.</p>\n\n      <h3>Important functions and sections</h3>\n      <ul><li><code>CheckPossible</code> - EM4 calls this before showing or allowing the command. It is usually where the script checks the caller type, equipment state, health, vehicle state, or whether the command should be greyed out.</li><li><code>CheckTarget</code> - EM4 calls this after the player points the command at something. This is where the script decides whether the clicked target is valid.</li><li><code>PushActions</code> - This is the execution stage. The script normally clears or appends actions here, then sends the caller toward a target, plays an animation, creates/removes objects, or triggers a dummy follow-up command.</li></ul>\n      <p><strong>Child command IDs:</strong> none detected. This script may use separate command objects instead of childID branches.</p>\n\n      <h3>Constants and state names</h3>\n      <p>Constants are the names the author uses so paths, command names, VO names, and states do not have to be typed repeatedly. When debugging, check these first because one typo can stop a command from appearing or a VO from being found.</p>\n      <p>No obvious constants were detected.</p>\n\n      <h3>Menu, icons, and command wiring</h3>\n      <p>These entries explain how the script connects to the visible command menu and to other commands. Icons and cursors must exist as matching DDS files in the correct UI folders.</p>\n      <p><strong>Icons:</strong></p><p>No SetIcon calls detected.</p>\n      <p><strong>Cursors:</strong></p><p>No SetCursor calls detected.</p>\n      <p><strong>Commands assigned:</strong></p><p>No AssignCommand calls detected.</p>\n      <p><strong>Commands removed:</strong></p><p>No RemoveCommand calls detected.</p>\n      <p><strong>Commands executed:</strong></p><p>No ExecuteCommand calls detected.</p>\n\n      <h3>Action queue behavior</h3>\n      <p>PushAction calls are the core of most EM4 scripts. They tell the engine what the actor should do over time: move, turn, wait, enter, exit, play animation, install equipment, shoot, or run a dummy follow-up step.</p>\n      <ul><li><code>PushActions</code></li></ul>\n\n      <h3>SDK calls used</h3>\n      <p>These are the engine API calls the script relies on. They are the best bridge between the SDK reference and the real mod behavior.</p>\n      <p><strong>Game namespace:</strong></p><p>No Game:: calls detected.</p>\n      <p><strong>Mission namespace:</strong></p><p>No Mission:: calls detected.</p>\n      <p><strong>ScriptInterface namespace:</strong></p><p>No ScriptInterface:: calls detected.</p>\n      <p><strong>Common object state calls:</strong></p><ul><li><code>IsValid</code></li></ul>\n\n      <h3>Assets and map dependencies</h3>\n      <p>These are the external things this script expects to exist. If one is missing, the script may fail, show a red X, do nothing, or crash depending on where it is used.</p>\n      <p><strong>Prototype references:</strong></p><p>No prototype paths detected.</p>\n      <p><strong>Audio references:</strong></p><p>No audio paths detected.</p>\n      <p><strong>Likely VO, object, path, station, or map-name references:</strong></p><p>No obvious map/object name references detected by the scanner.</p>\n\n      <h3>Restrictions and targeting rules</h3>\n      <p>Restrictions control who can use the command and what the command can target. If the button is missing, greyed out, or shows a red X, this is one of the first sections to inspect.</p>\n      <ul><li><code>RESTRICT_SELFEXECUTE</code></li><li><code>ACTOR_PERSON</code></li></ul>\n\n      <h3>How to debug this script</h3>\n      <ul>\n        <li>First confirm the script file loads without a logfile parser error.</li>\n        <li>Then confirm the prototype has the right command name assigned in the editor.</li>\n        <li>If the button appears but cannot be used, inspect <code>CheckPossible</code>, <code>CheckTarget</code>, restrictions, and required dummy commands.</li>\n        <li>If the actor moves but the sequence stops, follow the <code>PushAction</code> chain and any dummy command executed after a delay.</li>\n        <li>If a station, callout, alarm, or deployable cannot find something, verify the exact prototype path, VO name, object name, path name, icon name, and audio path listed above.</li>\n      </ul>\n    "
